{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"649b125a-1744-4510-b1ca-13e8e12137ad","content":"`dotnet-trace` only captures **managed** stacks. For native frames (interop libraries), use Linux **`perf`** instead — it captures both native and managed call stacks.\n\n### Steps\n\n**1. Enable managed symbol maps** (so `perf` can resolve .NET method names):\n\n```bash\n# Set before launching your app\nexport DOTNET_PerfMapEnabled=1\nexport DOTNET_EnablePerfMap=1\n```\n\nThen restart your application.\n\n**2. Install `perf`:**\n\n```bash\napt-get install linux-tools-$(uname -r)\n```\n\n**3. Record a CPU profile** (with call stacks):\n\n```bash\n# Profile for 30 seconds; -g enables call-graph capture\nperf record -g -p $(pidof your-app) -- sleep 30\n```\n\n**4. View the trace:**\n\n```bash\nperf script | less          # raw stacks (native + managed interleaved)\nperf report --call-graph    # interactive TUI summary\n```\n\nYou'll see both your native interop library frames **and** the managed .NET frames in the same call stacks.\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Symbols for your native lib**: install or keep debug symbols (`.so` with `-g` or separate `.debug` files) so `perf` resolves function names instead of raw addresses.\n- **Flame graphs** are great for visualizing mixed stacks:\n  ```bash\n  perf script | stackcollapse-perf.pl | flamegraph.pl > flame.svg\n  ```\n  (from [Brendan Gregg's FlameGraph tools](https://github.com/brendangregg/FlameGraph))","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94c71f65-354f-4098-9609-91c0852807eb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to capture native call stacks in a .NET 8 application running on Linux. This is a diagnostics/performance question, not a code change request. I should provide a concise, practical answer.\n\nKey points for getting native call stacks in .NET on Linux:\n\n1. Use `dotnet-trace` with the right event providers, but by default it only captures managed stacks.\n2. For native call stacks, you need to use `perf` (Linux perf) which can capture both managed and native stacks.\n3. Alternatively, `dotnet-trace` can be used with `--clreventlevel` but it won't give native frames.\n\n\n4. For `perf`, the best approach is to record with the `-g` flag to capture call graphs, and enable managed symbol resolution by setting the `DOTNET_PerfMapEnabled` environment variable so perf can resolve managed frames alongside native ones.\n5. `dotnet-trace` with CPU sampling will give you managed stacks but won't include native frames, so it's not ideal for native interop diagnostics.","outputTokens":899,"requestId":"D819:1D9368:828657:96597D:69FBEA2D"},"id":"c0c46ef4-d6f1-48f5-83b8-73c8eb42051f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:26:27.688Z","parentId":"e43edeb7-8588-4487-9cb2-01f58ce75089"}
